  footnotes: []
english:
  title: On the Road
  author: Sung Im
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Layered peaks and cascading ridges—fit only for a painter's brush.
    From sheer cliffs pour a hundred streams in every direction.
    Crimson leaves adorn the gorge after frost arrives,
    White clouds lock away the sky deep within the cave.

    Among such wonders, my eyes wander often,
    And when I compose brief verses, my shoulders rise with awe.
    Indifferent to the world's constant passage through here,
    The mountain monk sits wrapped in his tattered robe, idle and at peace each day.
  footnotes:
    - The poem contrasts the poet's aesthetic appreciation and spiritual absorption in nature with the indifference of ordinary travelers passing through the same landscape.
    - The mountain monk mentioned in the final couplet may represent the poet's own aspirational state or a figure embodying spiritual detachment from worldly concerns.
    - The physical responses described—wandering eyes and rising shoulders—convey the body's involuntary reaction to encountering the sublime in nature.
